              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Under-Counter Bar Refrigerators</h3>
                <p>
                  Under-counter bar refrigerators are a popular choice for bars and restaurants due to their space-saving design and easy accessibility. These units fit snugly beneath the counter, allowing bartenders to quickly grab beverages and ingredients without leaving their station. Common repair needs for under-counter bar refrigerators include issues with the thermostat, which can lead to improper cooling and spoilage of stored items. Problems with the door seal are also frequent, resulting in energy loss and inefficient cooling. Regular maintenance, such as cleaning the condenser coils and checking the refrigerant levels, can help prevent these issues and ensure the unit operates efficiently.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Back Bar Coolers</h3>
                <p>
                  Back bar coolers are designed to store and display beverages behind the bar, providing easy access for bartenders and an attractive display for customers. These coolers often feature glass doors and adjustable shelving, making them ideal for showcasing a variety of drinks. Common repair needs for back bar coolers include malfunctioning compressors, which can lead to inadequate cooling and potential beverage spoilage. Additionally, issues with the internal lighting system can affect the display's appeal. Routine maintenance, such as cleaning the evaporator fan and inspecting the door gaskets, can help keep back bar coolers running smoothly and looking their best.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Kegerators</h3>
                <p>
                  Kegerators are specialized refrigerators designed to store and dispense kegs of beer, making them a staple in many bars and restaurants. These units typically include a refrigeration system, a tap, and a CO2 tank to keep the beer carbonated and fresh. Common repair needs for kegerators include issues with the CO2 system, such as leaks or regulator malfunctions, which can affect the quality of the beer. Problems with the cooling system, such as a faulty thermostat or compressor, can also impact the beer's temperature and taste. Regular maintenance, including cleaning the beer lines and checking the CO2 levels, is essential to keep kegerators functioning properly and serving up perfect pints.
                </p>
